obo:BFO_0000066  a  owl:ObjectProperty .

dc:contributor  a  owl:AnnotationProperty .

gomodel:SYNGO_329  a      owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: This publication provides multiple lines of evidence that ELKS1 is localized to the presynaptic active zone.\n\n-In subcellular fractionation assays from synaptosomes, ELKS1 was detected in an insoluble fraction highly enriched in active zone markers RIM and liprin (figure 4A).\n-In confocal microscopy imaging, a large portion of ELKS signal overlapped with the presynaptic markers RIM and synapsin (figure 5A-B).\n-Using immuno electron microscopy, ELKS was detected at active zones in hippocampal slices (figure 5C), and additional signal was detected throughout the nerve terminal observed .\n\nNote that although the article refers to the antibody used for immunocytochemistry as ELKS1 specific, it recognizes both ELKS1 and ELKS2. Extensive characterization of the antibody, including knockout controls, is provided in Liu et.al. 2014 and Held et. al. 2016. ELKS1 and ELKS2 are both expressed at synapses in these cultures (Held et.al. 2016).. Experimental description: Double immunofluorescence labeling of cultured rat hippocampal neurons (12 days in vitro) was carried out essentially as described (22) by using affinity-purified ERC1b antibodies (p224) and monoclonal antibodies to RIM1\nor synapsin, with secondary antibodies coupled with Alexa Fluor 488 and 546 (Molecular Probes). Immunoelectron microscopy of brain sections was performed by using a preembedding 1.4-nm immunogold procedure with signal amplification with the HQ silver enhancement kit (Nanoprobes, Yaphank, NY) essentially as described (23)." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7620-2704" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1558-1958" ;
        dc:date           "2018-06-07" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_329" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

